<B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=5><P ALIGN="CENTER">Ind</FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=5>ices(Powers) Learning Plan 1</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER">Notation &amp; Rules</P>
</B></FONT><FONT FACE="Arial">
<P>While working through this plan you may find it helpful to refer to the lecture notes titled ‘Review of Indices’.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>When  multiplying the same quantity together several times, it is much more convenient to use powers rather than to write that quantity down each time, thus:</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER">3 x 3 = 3<SUP>2</SUP> = 9</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER">a x a = a<SUP>2</SUP> = a squared</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER">b x b x b = b<SUP>3</SUP> = b cubed</P>

<P>Remind yourself how to manipulate quantities raised to powers in <a href="runcal.htm#==k:\calmat\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 14 a~?">1-14 section a</a>, <a href="runcal.htm#==k:\calmat\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 14 b~?">section b</a> and <a href="runcal.htm#==k:\calmat\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 14 c~?">section c</a>.   Ensure you understand the Multiplication, Division and Power Rules.</P>

<P>Practise applying the Multiplication Rule in <a href="launch.htm#q0385">q0385</a>, <a href="launch.htm#q0388">q0388</a>, <a href="launch.htm#q0392">q0392</a>, <a href="launch.htm#q0605">q0605</a>, <a href="launch.htm#q0606">q0606</a>, <a href="launch.htm#q0032">q0032</a> and <a href="launch.htm#q0590">q0590</a>.   Use the Division Rule in <a href="launch.htm#q0390">q0390</a>, <a href="launch.htm#q0391">q0391</a> and <a href="launch.htm#q0386">q0386</a>.   Finally apply the Power Rule in <a href="launch.htm#q0389">q0389</a>, <a href="launch.htm#q0591">q0591</a>,<a href="launch.htm#q0649">q0649</a> and <a href="launch.htm#q0387">q0387</a>.</P>

<P>Indices or powers are used to make many business problems easier.   Consider the situation where you have £150 in the bank earning 8% interest.</P>

<P>At the end of the 1<SUP>st</SUP> Year you would have 150 + 150 x 0.08 = 150 x 1.08<SUP>1</P>
</SUP><P>At the end of the 2<SUP>nd</SUP> Year you would have 150 x 1.08<SUP>2</SUP> </P>
<P>At the end of the 3<SUP>rd</SUP> Year you would have 150 x 1.08<SUP>3</P>
<P>.&#9;&#9;.</P>
<P>.</P>
<P>.</P>
<P>.</P>
</SUP><P>At the end of the nth Year you would have 150 x 1.08<SUP>n</P>
</SUP>
<P>You may need to ask for help explaining this simplication however we will look in more detail at this result later in the semester.</P></FONT></BODY>
